<DOC><DOCNO> AP891213-0243 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-89 0152EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stLd-Writethru f0002 12-13 0762</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0002,0793</SECOND><HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS in first item, 2nd graf, to Tuesday, sted Thursday.</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Purchasing managers of the nation's corporationsthink the economy will avoid a recession next year but optimism hasebbed to the lowest level since the early 1980s.   The economy will be weak in the first half of 1990 and improveduring the remainder of the year, producing moderate growthoverall, the National Association of Purchasing Management said ina forecast released Tuesday.   Inflation will ease further next year and should finish thisyear milder than previously expected, the report said.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Bush administration, striving to meetdeficit-reduction targets without a tax increase, is preparing tobase its upcoming budget on an optimistic forecast showing 1990economic growth far higher than many private estimates,administration sources said.   The sources said Tuesday that the administration is expected toforecast that the economy, as measured by the gross nationalproduct, will expand by 2.6 percent next year.   The administration's GNP figure is based on anticipated growthfrom the fourth quarter of this year to the fourth quarter of 1990.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Times Mirror Inc. says it is unlikely to havehigher operating earnings this year, partly due to a weakadvertising market for newspapers in the Northeast.   Separately, The New York Times Co. on Tuesday announced a $44million charge against fourth-quarter earnings due to itsinvestment in its forest products operation and estimated costsrelated to expected voluntary union staff cuts at The New YorkTimes, its flagship newspaper.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Labor Department is proposing $3.3 millionin fines against a Philadelphia plant for 840 alleged safetyviolations, including failure to tell some workers that testsshowed their hearing was deteriorating.   Most of the citations issued Tuesday to the Budd Co. by thedepartment's Occupational Safety and Health Administration allegedviolations either of noise- and hearing-related standards orrequirements that employers keep detailed records of workplaceinjuries.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush has signed legislationextending restraints on steel imports through April 1992.   The measure signed Tuesday by the president renews restrictionson 29 foreign trading partners that had expired Oct. 1. Bush alsosaid major foreign steel-producing nations had reached voluntaryagreements with the United States on steel trade.</TEXT><DATELINE>SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ramada Inc. shareholders have approveda corporate restructuring plan that includes the sale of thechain's 800 hotels to a Hong Kong company.   The restructuring, approved Tuesday at a special shareholders'meeting in Scottsdale, also will create a new company, Aztar Corp.,to operate Ramada's Nevada and New Jersey casinos.   New World Hotel (Holdings) Ltd. of Hong Kong will pay Ramadaabout $540 million for the hotel business.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The administration says it may lift bans on``normal commercial exports'' to China, including satellites thatnation would launch, after reviewing sanctions imposed after theviolent crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators.   The administration said Tuesday it is specifically looking atthree Hughes Aircraft communication satellites, one due for launchby China in April and the others in 1991 and 1992, that were heldup by Bush's ban on export of weapons and satellites to China lastJune.</TEXT><DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Deutsche Bank has named HilmarKopper as its new chairman to succeed Alfred Herrhausen, who waskilled in a terrorist attack Nov. 30.   Kopper, 54, had been widely mentioned as the most likelysuccessor to Herrhausen to head West Germany's largest bank. Theposting was announced Tuesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Numerous violations of environmental laws byoil and gas developers go undetected under a federal leasingprogram, and even when found rarely result in penalties, accordingto an internal Interior Department investigation.   The report by the department's Inspector General's Office saidthat the federal Bureau of Land Management's scrutiny of oil andgas leases is inadequate to force lease operators to comply withenvironmental requirements or assure proper royalty payments to thegovernment.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market closed higher Tuesday after a late-afternoonrally led by the energy sector. The Dow Jones industrial averagegained 23.89 to close at 2,752.13.   The dollar hit a one-year low against West Germany's mark inboth New York and Europe.   Bond prices were little changed in light trading.   Gold futures prices inched nearer to new highs for the year;silver futures slipped; oil futures were mostly lower; grains andsoybeans were mixed; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>